<task id="040" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5">
  <metadata>
    <title>D3-01 `/analyze` configuration-only proof point (validates SC-19 platform-extension claim)</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <actual-effort></actual-effort>
    <assigned>AI Agent</assigned>
    <started></started>
    <completed></completed>
    <phase>Phase 3 — Polish + Future-Use Validation</phase>
    <wave>P3-1 (serial; proof-point validation; first task of Phase 3)</wave>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>Phase 2 ✅ (specifically tasks 010 action-seed pattern + 015 tool-registration pattern + 017 StructuredOutputStreamWidget + 019 slash-command pattern + 031 verification)</dependencies>
    <tags>dataverse, seed, playbook, proof-point, validation</tags>
    <rigor-level>FULL</rigor-level>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Ship a configuration-only `/analyze` follow-on playbook to validate the SC-19
    platform-extension claim: that NEW playbook capabilities ship via configuration
    (action seed + playbook config + tool registration + slash-command entry) and NOT
    via new orchestration code. This task is BOTH a deliverable (new `/analyze`
    capability) AND a load-bearing measurement (does R5's "configuration-first"
    architecture hold up when a second playbook is added?). Per SC-19, the entire
    end-to-end cost MUST be &lt; 1 day; per plan.md Phase 3 estimate, &lt; 4 hours.
    Time/cost MUST be tracked + documented in task notes to substantiate the claim.

    The task mirrors the D2-03 (orchestrator) + D2-05 (tool wrapper) + D2-10 (slash
    command) patterns established by Phase 2, but at MINIMAL incremental cost:
    (a) ONE new `sprk_analysisaction` seed (`ANALYZE-DOC@v1`) deployed via the
    EXISTING `scripts/Deploy-Playbook.ps1` harness (or its task-010 extension); (b) a
    MINIMAL tool wrapper class that DELEGATES to a reused orchestrator pattern (per
    R5 §3.1 reuse mandate — prefer parameterizing `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` over
    introducing a parallel orchestrator; if parameterization is infeasible, author
    `SessionAnalyzeOrchestrator` as a thin delegate that shares the streaming
    infrastructure from tasks 005/006); (c) tool registration on the EXISTING
    `SprkChatAgent` via the EXISTING `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` mechanism;
    (d) one new `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS` entry (`/analyze`); (e) output rendering via
    the EXISTING `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` (task 017) — proving the widget IS
    schema-driven and IS reusable across playbooks, not Summarize-specific.

    R5 §3.1 prohibited list applies in full: NO new prompt-bearing entity (the
    action row IS the JPS prompt primitive per §10 gotcha); NO new chat agent; NO
    new orchestration layer paralleling `AnalysisOrchestrationService`; NO new
    widget paralleling `StructuredOutputStreamWidget`; NO new SSE envelope (the
    `FieldDelta` variant from task 005 carries `/analyze` output identically); NO
    new feature flag (per §3.2 — register unconditionally inside existing
    capability-gated tool block; kill-switch inherits via `NullSprkChatAgentFactory`).
    BFF publish-size delta target: ≤ +0.1 MB. If this task's delta exceeds +0.5 MB,
    the SC-19 "configuration-only" claim is at risk — escalate per R5 §6.

    Crucially: a FAILED proof point is itself a valid SC-19 finding. If the
    implementation surfaces a forced parallel orchestrator, a forced parallel
    widget, or a delta substantially above target, STOP and record the deviation in
    `notes/sc-19-proof-point-evidence.md` per CLAUDE.md §6 escalation — this is
    EVIDENCE for the platform-extension assessment, not a defect to silently mask.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior full-stack engineer with mastery across all R5 implementation surfaces:
    Dataverse data deploys via `scripts/Deploy-Playbook.ps1` (per task 010 pattern),
    JPS prompt + JSON Schema authoring (per task 010 Step 3–4 pattern), the
    `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` tool-registration site (per task 015
    pattern), the `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS` slash-command surface + ConversationPane
    intent-handler (per task 019 pattern), and the `StructuredOutputStreamWidget`
    schema-driven render contract (per task 017 pattern). Capable of reasoning about
    measurement discipline (time tracking + publish-size measurement) as
    first-class deliverables, not afterthoughts.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A new `/analyze` playbook capability is live end-to-end on Spaarke Dev with
    total implementation cost &lt; 1 day (≤ 4 hours target per plan.md), fully
    measured and documented:
    (a) A new `sprk_analysisaction` row `ANALYZE-DOC@v1` ("Analyze Document for
        Chat") exists in Spaarke Dev Dataverse — deployed via the EXISTING
        `scripts/Deploy-Playbook.ps1` (or its task-010 extension), carrying a
        JPS-formatted `sprk_systemprompt` + structured-outputs-compatible JSON
        schema; deploy is idempotent (lookup-by-`sprk_actioncode` skip-on-exists);
    (b) A new `sprk_analysisplaybook` row `analyze-for-chat@v1` references the
        action via `actionCode = 'ANALYZE-DOC@v1'`;
    (c) A MINIMAL `InvokeAnalyzePlaybookTool` class is registered on the EXISTING
        `SprkChatAgent` via `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools`, delegating to a
        reused orchestrator (prefer parameterized `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator`
        per R5 §3.1; sibling `SessionAnalyzeOrchestrator` only if parameterization
        is infeasible — decision recorded with rationale);
    (d) A new `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS` entry for `/analyze` is added in
        `slashCommandMenu.types.ts` + wired in the ConversationPane intent-handler
        (mirroring task 019's `/summarize` pattern);
    (e) Output renders progressively via the EXISTING `StructuredOutputStreamWidget`
        (task 017) — NO new widget, NO modifications to the widget beyond
        schema-driven extension points that already exist. This is the load-bearing
        proof that the widget is genuinely schema-driven (NFR-12 / SC-19);
    (f) Slash-command path (`/analyze`) + natural-language tool-call path
        (LLM tool-calls `InvokeAnalyzePlaybook`) BOTH work end-to-end on Spaarke Dev
        and produce structured output rendered in the Workspace pane via SSE
        `FieldDelta` events;
    (g) Total elapsed implementation time is tracked from Step 0 start to Step 10
        complete and recorded in task notes as the SC-19 measurement;
    (h) BFF publish-size delta is measured + recorded (target ≤ +0.1 MB; escalation
        threshold +0.5 MB);
    (i) `code-review` + `adr-check` quality gates pass at Step 9.5;
    (j) Task notes (`notes/sc-19-proof-point-evidence.md`) substantiate the SC-19
        claim with: elapsed cost, files modified count, lines-of-code delta, BFF
        publish-size delta, decision log (orchestrator parameterize vs sibling),
        widget-reuse evidence (StructuredOutputStreamWidget rendered `/analyze`
        output without modification), and any divergences from the
        "configuration-only" target.
  </goal>

