        per task 010's preferred path), Step 6-9 (dry-run, live deploy, verify,
        idempotency-rerun). Action code: `ANALYZE-DOC@v1` (mnemonic `ANALYZE-DOC`;
        version `@v1`).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Playbook config row (binding template from task 011)" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/011-sprk-analysisplaybook-summarize-config.poml">
        Task 011 is the canonical template for the playbook-row half. Mirror its
        playbook + node-rows structure: ONE playbook row (`analyze-for-chat@v1`
        referencing `actionCode = 'ANALYZE-DOC@v1'`) with ONE primary LLM-analysis
        node bound to the action row. Use the same `Deploy-Playbook.ps1` extension
        path task 011 already established. Idempotency mirrors task 011.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Minimal tool wrapper (binding template from task 015)" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/015-invoke-summarize-playbook-tool.poml">
        Task 015's `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool` is the canonical shape for
        `InvokeAnalyzePlaybookTool`. Mirror: `public sealed class`; constructor
        accepts the orchestrator + scoped state; method
        `InvokeAnalyzePlaybookAsync(string[]? fileIds, string? style, CancellationToken ct)`
        decorated with `[Description("...")]`; `public IEnumerable&lt;AIFunction&gt; GetTools()`
        yielding `AIFunctionFactory.Create(...)`; registered inside
        `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` in a sibling capability-gated block to
        the Summarize block (lines 807–834 reference per task 015 Step 5). The
        delegation target is the parameterized `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` (with
        playbook-code argument `analyze-for-chat@v1`) OR the new
        `SessionAnalyzeOrchestrator` per the Step 3 decision.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Slash command extension (binding template from task 019)" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/019-slash-command-summarize-semantic-extension.poml">
        Task 019 is the canonical template for the slash-command half. Mirror:
        ONE-line edit to `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS` in `slashCommandMenu.types.ts`
        ADDING a new `/analyze` entry adjacent to `/summarize`; one ConversationPane
        intent-handler branch routing `/analyze` to `InvokeAnalyzePlaybook` (via
        the chat-agent natural-language path) OR to the direct endpoint
        (if a `POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{id}/analyze` endpoint is added — note
        below).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Widget reuse evidence (proof for SC-19)" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/017-structured-output-stream-widget.poml">
        `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` MUST render `/analyze` output WITHOUT
        modification. Verify by: (a) reviewing the widget's schema-driven render
        extension points (it consumes `FieldDelta.Path` events and maps them to
        renderers via a schema-keyed registry); (b) confirming `/analyze` output
        fields (e.g., `analysisSummary`, `keyFindings`, `risks`, `recommendations`)
        are renderable via the existing renderer registry OR via the widget's
        default-renderer fallback. If a new renderer is required, record as a
        DEVIATION from the configuration-only claim in `notes/sc-19-proof-point-evidence.md`
        — the deviation is itself valid SC-19 evidence (the widget is not yet 100%
        schema-driven; partial credit for SC-19).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Direct endpoint scope decision" location="design rationale">
        The PROOF POINT scope is the natural-language tool-call path (LLM
        tool-calls `InvokeAnalyzePlaybook`) + the slash-command path. A direct
        endpoint (`POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{id}/analyze`) is NOT strictly
        required for SC-19. PREFERRED: skip the direct endpoint to keep cost &lt; 4
        hours. If the slash-command intent-handler routes `/analyze` to the
        agent-tool path (mirroring task 019's tri-mode `/summarize` routing where
        natural-language → tool-call), the agent tool covers BOTH invocation
        modes. Record the decision + rationale in task notes.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Phase 3 of R5 has one binding job: PROVE the platform-extension claim
      (design.md §6.1 + spec SC-19). The claim is: "R5 ships a chat-driven
      Summarize vertical slice as the FIRST playbook on a generalized configuration
      surface; subsequent playbooks (`/analyze`, `/compare`, `/translate`,
      `/extract`) ship via configuration alone — action seed + playbook config +
      tool registration + slash command — without new orchestration code, new
      widgets, or new SSE envelopes." If this claim holds, R5's architecture
      investment compounds across R6+ playbook backlog (cheap to add new
      capabilities). If it FAILS — if `/analyze` forces a parallel orchestrator,
      a parallel widget, or a substantial publish-size jump — R5's architecture
      claim is partially or fully invalidated, and the lessons-learned doc
      (task 044 / D3-05) MUST capture that honestly.

      `/analyze` is the chosen proof point because it's (a) semantically distinct
      from `/summarize` (different output schema, different intent), (b) on the
      R6+ backlog regardless, and (c) cheap enough to validate within Phase 3's
      0.5-week budget. If `/analyze` ships cleanly in &lt; 4 hours with no new
      orchestrator + no widget changes + publish-size delta ≤ +0.1 MB, SC-19 is
      proven. If any of those three constraints is violated, SC-19 is partially
      proven and the deviation IS the lesson.

      This task is the SECOND application of the action-seed + tool-wrapper +
      slash-command pattern (the first was tasks 010 + 015 + 019 in Phase 2 for
      Summarize). Phase 2 established the template; Phase 3 tests its
      reproducibility at marginal cost. The task is intentionally serial (P3-1
      single task) because its measurement value depends on it being a fresh
      attempt — not parallelized with Phase 3's other deliverables (Get Started
      card, telemetry dashboards) which have independent value.
    </background>
